\begin_layout Standard
There are several approaches in the literature that address solving the
 service-coverage problem in radio networks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nawrocki_Understanding:2006,Siomina_Pilot.power.optimization:2004"

\end_inset

.
 Some of them even claim to achieve near-optimal solutions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Siomina:Minimum.pilot.power.for.service.coverage"

\end_inset

.
 As a matter of fact, most formulations are only useful for small network
 instances and often fail when challenged with larger and real-world networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A genetic-algorithm approach for solving the service-coverage problem for
 GSM networks is presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lieska-Radion_coverage_optimization_with_genetic_algorithms:1998"

\end_inset

.
 The proposed solution is based on the physical distribution of base-station
 antennas in order to maximize coverage.
 The simulations were performed on a test network with 40 candidate sites
 for base-station antennas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Siomina:Minimum.pilot.power.for.service.coverage"

\end_inset

, Siomina and Yuan considered the problem of minimizing the total amount
 of pilot power for UMTS networks subject to a full coverage constraint.
 They tackled the problem with an iterative linear-programming approach,
 reporting very good results for some test networks, containing from 15
 to 65 base stations.
 The authors noted that bigger problem instances could not be solved because
 of hardware constraints on the target platform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for LTE networks, the service-coverage problem is presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Thampi-A_sparse_sampling_algorithm_for_self_optimisation_of_coverage_in_LTE_networks:2012"

\end_inset

.
 The authors presented an algorithm, based on reinforcement learning, to
 tackle three aspects of the coverage problem, i.e., coverage holes, weak
 coverage and pilot pollution.
 The experimental simulations, performed on 3 base stations, used different
 antenna-tilt configurations as the proposed solutions.
 The service-coverage problem as presented in this chapter corresponds to
 achieving full coverage of the target area, i.e., without coverage holes.
\end_layout

