\begin_layout Section
Problem definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the problem of optimization of pilot powers for service coverage, the
 objective is to find a set of pilot power settings for all cells in the
 network, such that the total pilot power used is minimized, and a given
 service coverage criteria is fulfilled.
 In other words, solving the service-coverage problem corresponds to finding
 the pilot power levels 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}$
\end_inset

, for all cells 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in C$
\end_inset

, such that coverage of at least 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 mobiles is guaranteed, while the total amount of pilot power used is minimized.
 Here, full coverage of the service area is being considered, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\vert M\vert$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, the optimization objective is defined as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{*}=\min\sum_{c\in C}p_{c},\label{eq:06-Objective_function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
subject to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\sum_{m\in M}cov(c_{m}^{*},m)}{b}=1.\label{eq:06-Coverage_constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been proved that the problem of pilot-power optimization for full
 coverage of the service area is 
\begin_inset Formula $NP$
\end_inset

-hard, since it can be reduced to the set-covering problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Varbrand_Mathematical.programming.approach:2003"

\end_inset

.
 Consequently, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $P\neq NP$
\end_inset

, it is unfeasible that a polynomial-time algorithm exists, which is able
 to find an exact solution to this problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimization approaches 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:06-Optimization-approaches"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since some of the analyzed problem instances are part of a real mobile network
 deployed in Slovenia by Telekom Slovenije, d.d., there are no references
 in the literature of other optimization techniques dealing with exactly
 the same data set.
 For this reason, two different strategies for setting the pilot power are
 being presented.
 They should provide a basis for the comparisson of the experimental results.
 The first strategy is the attenuation-based pilot power, presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Siomina_Pilot.power.optimization:2004"

\end_inset

, in which a pixel of the service area is always covered by the cell with
 the maximum attenuation-factor value, i.e., the minimum path loss.
 The second strategy is the presented parallel-agent approach, based on
 ideas inspired by two-dimensional cellular automata 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sarkar_Cellular.automata.history:2000"

\end_inset

 and metaheuristics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Talbi_Metaheuristics:2009"

\end_inset

.
 A detailed description is given in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:06-Parallel_agent_approach"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar criteria for result comparison have also been used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Siomina:Minimum.pilot.power.for.service.coverage"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Attenuation-based approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first heuristic for setting the pilot power of all cells in the network
 is known as attenuation-based, since it relies on the downlink-attenuation
 factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{cm}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset

.
 A mobile located on some pixel of the service area is always covered by
 the cell with the maximum 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{cm}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset

.
 Whenever the maximum available power, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}^{k}$
\end_inset

, is the same for all the cells in the network, this is equivalent to selecting
 the cell with the minimum required pilot power to cover a mobile 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, under this assumption, the cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 covering mobile 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is identified as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{cm}^{\mathrm{att}}=\min p_{c}\forall c\in C\iff cov(c,m)=1\label{eq:06-Attenuation_based-power}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Picking the cells conforming to Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:06-Attenuation_based-power"

\end_inset

) and setting the pilot powers accordingly, full coverage of the service
 area is achieved.
 The solution exhibits a total pilot power defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{\mathrm{att}}=\sum_{c\in C}\max p_{cm}^{\mathrm{att}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The procedure to find a cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 for every mobile 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in the service area consists in sorting, in descending order, all mobiles
 by their attenuation-factor values, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{cm}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset

.
 The solution is thus established by the first 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 mobiles of the sorted sequence, taking the maximum pilot-power setting
 for a cell into account, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{cm}^{\mathrm{att}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Parallel-agent approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:06-Parallel_agent_approach"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the parallel-agent approach, a set of autonomous worker agents explore
 the target geographical area, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{total}}$
\end_inset

, in order to optimize the pilot-power consumption.
 Each agent randomly moves over the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{total}}$
\end_inset

 as it dictates different changes to the pilot power of the cells.
 PRATO, the radio-coverage framework presented in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
